41 /* There is no portable way in C99 to printf 64-bit types. Many
42  * platforms do have a format which will do it, but it's not
43  * standardized. Therefore these macros.
44  *
45  * Not all platforms using gnu C necessarily have a corresponding
46  * printf, but it's probably a good starting point. Most unix systems
47  * seem to use %ll.
48  */
49 #if SIZEOF_LONG == 8
50 # define PRINTF_CAST_U64(x) ((unsigned long) (x))
51 # define PRINTF_FORMAT_U64 "%lu"
52 #elif defined(__GNUC__)
53 # define PRINTF_CAST_U64(x) ((unsigned long long) (x))
54 # define PRINTF_FORMAT_U64 "%llu"
55 #else
56  /* This conversion works everywhere, but it's probably pretty slow.
57  *
58  * Note that 'f' takes a double vararg, not a float. */
59 # define PRINTF_CAST_U64(x) ((double) (x))
60 # define PRINTF_FORMAT_U64 "%.0f"
61 #endif
62

64 #if defined(HAVE_VARARG_MACROS) && defined(__GNUC__)

77 #ifdef DO_RS_TRACE
78 # define rs_trace(fmt, arg...) \
79  do { rs_log0(RS_LOG_DEBUG, __FUNCTION__, fmt , ##arg); \
80  } while (0)
